Data Visualization with Pandas¶

Pythons popular data analysis library, pandas, provides several different options for visualizing your data with .plot(). Even if youre at the beginning of your pandas journey, youll soon be creating basic plots that will yield valuable insights into your data.

In this session, we are going to visualize data on college majors sourced from the American Community Survey 20102012 Public Use Microdata Sample.

In [1]:
import pandas as pd
In [2]:
df = pd.read_csv('./recent-grads.csv')

inline backend for matplotlib is popular for Jupyter Notebooks because it displays the plot in the notebook itself, immediately below the cell that creates the plot:

In [4]:
%matplotlib inline

"Median" is the median earnings of full-time, year-round workers and "Rank" is the majors rank by median earnings.

Lets start with a plot displaying these columns.

Now youre ready to make your first plot! You can do so with .plot():

In [5]:
df.plot(x="Rank", y="Median")
Out[5]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='Rank'>

.plot() returns a line graph containing data from every row in the DataFrame. The x-axis values represent the rank of each institution, and the "Median" values are plotted on the y-axis.

Looking at the plot, you can make the following observations:

The median income decreases as rank decreases. This is expected because the rank is determined by the median income.

.plot() has several optional parameters. Most notably, the kind parameter accepts eleven different string values and determines which kind of plot youll create:

  • "area" is for area plots.
  • "bar" is for vertical bar charts.
  • "barh" is for horizontal bar charts.
  • "hist" is for histograms.
  • "density" is an alias for "kde".
  • "line" is for line graphs.
  • "pie" is for pie charts.
  • "scatter" is for scatter plots.

The default value is "line". Line graphs, like the one you created above, provide a good overview of your data. You can use them to detect general trends.

.plot() is a wrapper for pyplot.plot(), and the result is a graph identical to the one you produced with Matplotlib:

In [6]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

plt.plot(df["Rank"], df["Median"])
Out[6]:
[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x7fa1546949e8>]

A histogram is a good way to visualize how values are distributed across a dataset. Histograms group values into bins and display a count of the data points whose values are in a particular bin.

Lets create a histogram for the "Median" column:

In [7]:
df["Median"].plot(kind="hist")
Out[7]:
<AxesSubplot:ylabel='Frequency'>

The histogram shows the data grouped into ten bins ranging from 20,000 to 120,000, and each bin has a width of 10,000.

The histogram of the median data, however, peaks on the left below 40,000. The tail stretches far to the right and suggests that there are indeed fields whose majors can expect significantly higher earnings.

Lets create a new DataFrame called top_5by selecting the five majors with the highest median earnings:

In [8]:
top_5 = df.sort_values(by="Median", ascending=False).head()

Now you have a smaller DataFrame containing only the top five most lucrative majors. As a next step, you can create a bar plot that shows only the majors with these top five median salaries:

In [10]:
top_5.plot(x="Major", y="Median", kind="bar", rot=90)
Out[10]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='Major'>

This plot shows that the median salary of petroleum engineering majors is more than 20,000 USD higher than the rest. The earnings for the second- through fourth-place majors are relatively close to one another.

Lets investigate all majors whose median salary is above 60,000 USD. First, you need to filter these majors with the mask df[df["Median"] > 60000]. Then you can create another bar plot showing all three earnings columns:

In [11]:
top_medians = df[df["Median"] > 60000].sort_values("Median")
In [12]:
top_medians.plot(x="Major", y="Median", kind="bar")
Out[12]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='Major'>

Often you want to see whether two columns of a dataset are connected. If you pick a major with higher median earnings, do you also have a lower chance of unemployment? As a first step, create a scatter plot with those two columns:

In [13]:
df.plot(x="Median", y="Unemployment_rate", kind="scatter")
Out[13]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='Median', ylabel='Unemployment_rate'>

A quick glance at this figure shows that theres no significant correlation between the earnings and unemployment rate.

Many datasets already contain some explicit or implicit categorization. In the current example, the 173 majors are divided into 16 categories.

A basic usage of categories is grouping and aggregation. You can use .groupby() to determine how popular each of the categories in the college major dataset are:

In [14]:
cat_totals = df.groupby("Major_category")["Total"].sum().sort_values()
cat_totals

With .groupby(), you create a DataFrameGroupBy object. With .sum(), you create a Series.

Lets draw a horizontal bar plot showing all the category totals in cat_totals:

In [15]:
cat_totals.plot(kind="barh",figsize=(5, 8))
Out[15]:
<AxesSubplot:ylabel='Major_category'>

As your plot shows, business is by far the most popular major category. While humanities and liberal arts is the clear second, the rest of the fields are more similar in popularity.

If youre interested in ratios, then pie plots are an excellent tool.

In [16]:
cat_totals.plot(kind="pie",label="",figsize=(5, 5))
Out[16]:
<AxesSubplot:>
